ecisions are currently made for medicare it also suggests some ways to incorporate the principles underlying comparative effectiveness research cer into cms decisionmaking  the arcane procedures that are part of currentlaw policy are important to understanding the stovepiped nature of medicare payments as well as some of the peculiar outcomes of the current system the complexity of the coverage and reimbursement specifics that are produced with these different calculations are breathtaking  fixing these problems is—well—daunting at best as pearson and bach remind us decisions regarding coverage and reimbursement reflect a lot of history  coverage may reflect a national decision for coverage or may follow the local coverage decisions of various carriers  on occasion congress directs medicare to cover a disease or procedure such as they did with end stage renal disease  reimbursement decisions are much more complicated than coverage decisions and the structure that they follow tends to be settingspecific which is why the same service that is performed in different settings can be reimbursed so differently  for more than a decade — including the time when i chaired the medicare payment advisory commission — medpac commissioners and others have been expressing frustration at this inconsistency rehab services provided in nursing homes versus rehab services provided in other settings has been a frequently cited example  similar problems exist whenever the same service is provided in multiple settings  while it would be possible to “force” a common reimbursement across settings if done in isolation this would distort whatever relationship exists between the service involved and the various other services provided within the same setting  redoing entire reimbursement systems even when there is widespread agreement that they are fundamentally flawed is extremely difficult as evidenced by our current struggles over the sustainable growth rate and the medicare physician fee schedule proposed strategy despite the significant differences in how medicare reimbursement strategies are designed as pearson and bach note medicare reimbursement generally reflects the cost of the service directly or based on historical estimates that are then periodically updated basically the strategy that pearson and bach propose for incorporating comparative effectiveness research into reimbursement would only change medicare’s reliance on cost as the basis for reimbursement in a limited way  reimbursement would continue to reflect cost but for those services or products that are found to be clinically comparable to an existing service or product the reimbursement would reflect the cost of the comparable service or product rather than its own cost  this is similar to reference pricing a reimbursement strategy that is used frequently in other countries particularly for pharmaceuticals  it is also similar to a strategy that is used occasionally in medicare known as “least costly alternative” where reimbursement may be limited to the reimbursement for a lower priced product  it is my understanding that there has been considerable dispute about how and when cms can make use of the “least costly alternative” principle and in some instances congress and the courts have intervened and prohibited its use the innovation that pearson and bach bring is to explicitly tie the reimbursement of a new product or service to its comparative effectiveness relative to an existing product or service  those that can be shown to be clinically “superior” would be reimbursed using the customary costrelated reimbursement strategy  those that were not clinically superior would be reimbursed at the existing comparable product’s level  those for which there is insufficient evidence would be reimbursed at the higher level that would normally be set for a new product for an initial three year period after which they would be reevaluated for evidence of clinical superiority  if clinical superiority can be demonstrated the higher price would continue otherwise the reimbursement would fall to the level of the competitor product i support the basic strategy pearson and bach present especially separating the relevance of cer for reimbursement as opposed to coverage  although some may argue that distinguishing lack of coverage from the lack of appropriate reimbursement is a difference without meaning conceptually the distinction is important  if the product or service is safe and effective it should be able to be provided however if it doesn’t do more than what is already on the market it’s not clear why there should be any higher payment  the principle is clear enough  establishing the answer empirically may be more of a challenge i’m not quite sure why pearson and bach seem so concerned about whether three years will be precisely the right period of time for all innovations  the answer is it will surely be inadequate for evaluating some innovations and perhaps generous for others  it seems to me that cms could be authorized to allow an additional twoyear extension of the original reimbursement whenever there appeared to be convincing evidence that the manufacturer had attempted to collect evidence in an expeditious way but that significant questions remained unanswered or unresolved after three years challenges the challenges are both technical and political  pearson and bach clearly appreciate the difficulties in defining what will be termed “superior” versus “comparable” clinical effectiveness  the discussion regarding the potential challenges of amassing an adequate base of evidence within  years also indicates that they are not underestimating the challenges associated with comparator measurements  they also recognize both the importance of and the difficulties associated with measuring patient preferences in establishing comparable or superior comparative clinical effectiveness  they also raise the question as to whether this approach should be only for new products and services or for existing ones as well the resolution of these as well as other technical and measurement issues will require greater consensus than now exists but should be aided by the methodology committee that was established by the affordable care act to advise the patientcentered outcomes research institute pcori  whatever views ultimately prevail any changes will need to go through the rulemaking process if they are to become a part of medicare reimbursement strategy assuming legislative authority is provided  given the controversial nature of these issues rulemaking is likely to be an arduous process  as to whether this approach should be used only for new products and services or existing ones as well a reasonable strategy is to start with new products and services in order to clearly establish the principle   over time however whenever there are several different products or services in the same space that are both highcost and highvolume an assessment to establish clinical superiority for the higher reimbursed products should also be undertaken  because the “pushback” for existing products is likely to be greater than for new products and services this assessment should only be undertaken after the principle of superior clinical effectiveness in exchange for higher reimbursement has been clearly established the technical issues involved with establishing superiority versus comparability in terms of clinical effectiveness are not likely to be as challenging as the political challenges  congress or at least some members of congress was skittish about including costeffectiveness analyses as part of cer as well as about how cer might ultimately be used this was reflected in the various provisions and limitations relating to cer in the economic stimulus legislation arra as well as in provisions in the affordable care act for example although pcori was not envisioned as a decisionmaking body the aca makes clear that it isn’t to mandate coverage reimbursement  etc  in addition to these prohibitions the language reflects the intent of the congress that evidence from research should be part of a larger process used for coverage decisions rather than the sole basis for such decisions and that evidence should not be used in such a way that benefits to people with disabilities would be assigned lower values  none of the prohibitions in the statutory language either of arra or the affordable care act directly relate to the use of a form of reference pricing that reflects clinical effectiveness comparability such as is being suggested  of course nothing in the statute allows it either and cms would need statutory authority to establish this type of reimbursement strategy as a sidebar in their discussion of the use of two prices for intensitymodulated radiation therapy one for higher risk patients and a lower one for other patients pearson and bach say that medicare has never tried making such differential payments but that is not quite accurate   when i was the hcfa administrator the agency was struggling about when to pay the higher costs associated with the use of low osmolardensity contrast material  the american college of radiology was asked or offered—i can’t remember which to identify the conditions where the use of the more expensive contrast medium was clinically important  in those cases a higher payment was made in all other cases payment was based on the lowercost contrast material although hospitals were free to use whichever contrast medium they preferred an alternative framework for using cer in medicare as i’ve indicated i support the strategy of not providing higher reimbursement for products and services that do not provide clinically superior outcomes or only providing higher reimbursements for the subgroups where superiority can be demonstrated  i also support the notion of providing a limited time frame for companies to be able to claim superiority without actually being able to prove it  companies that need more than three years could even be asked to assume partial risk for the differential payment  the question is whether there might be a concept that is more comfortable than pearson’s and bach’s framework for the congress and the public to use that also incorporates cer into medicare’s reimbursement policies what is the best way to push these ideas forward  my suggestion is to think about incorporating the concepts of cer into medicare reimbursement as part of the more general move to valuebased insurance and valuebased reimbursement rather than as a standalong change  the concept of valuebased reimbursement is present in several provisions of the affordable care act including the use of a valuebased purchasing for hospitals in  as well as the development of plans for valuebased purchasing for nursing homes home care and ambulatory surgical centers  limiting higher levels of reimbursement only to those services and products that have demonstrably superior clinical outcomes is completely consistent with the use of vbr and should be regarded as part of the more general move to vbr it would be even more useful to incorporate notions of valuebased insurance into this process  under vbi principles the lowest copayments would be used for those products and services that have the best clinical outcome in general or for a particular subset of the population  similarly products and services whose outcomes are highly uncertain or of less clinical value would have higher copayments  this type of tiered copayment is very familiar to the public since most insurance policies have used some variant of it for pharmaceutical benefits for more than a decade  the difference is that now the lowest coinsurance or copays would be for the services with the highest or more certain clinical outcomes just as the adoption of tiered copayments by part d medicare drug plans was a nonevent following several years of use by the private sector perhaps the adoption of tiered copayments reflecting comparative clinical effectiveness could become a nonevent for medicare if it were to be adopted first by the private sector  unlike medicare employers sponsoring coverage and private insurance companies don’t need the congress’ permission to adopt innovative payment strategies although the aca places some limits on changes that can be introduced by plans that wish to be considered as grandfathered thus to me the best way to incorporate cer into medicare reimbursement is to think of it as part of the move to vbi and vbr and to push hard for innovative employers and private sector insurance to begin adopting these principles as soon as possible  fortunately this seems to have been happening already as evidenced by some of the material in the november issue of health affairs associated topics costs and spending drugs and medical technology medicare payment policy tags comparative effectiveness medicare payment pharma spending technology leave a reply comment moderation is in use please do not submit your comment twice  it will appear shortly name required email will not be published required website receive an email if someone else comments on this post most recent most read senate parliamentarian rules several bcra provisions violate the byrd ruletimothy jost cbo’s estimates of the revised senate health billjoseph antos and james capretta orphan diseases or population health policy choices drive venture capital investmentsdayton misfeldt and james c robinson the latest cbo score of the better care reconciliation act leaves  million uninsured by  updatetimothy jost cms releases faq on its new proxy direct enrollment pathwaytimothy jost unpacking the senates take on aca repeal and replacetimothy jost and sara rosenbaum in senate health care bill a few hidden surprisesstan dorn and sara rosenbaum growth of acos and alternative payment models in david muhlestein robert saunders and mark mcclellan the senate health care billjoseph antos and james caprett